inputs.label: use_context
inputs.description: When true, include this run's active context messages (context.messages) as agent history. If the pin is not connected, the node checkbox is used. Default: false.

inputs.label: provider
inputs.description: LLM provider id (e.g. LMStudio). If unset, uses the node’s configured provider.

inputs.label: model
inputs.description: LLM model id/name. If unset, uses the node’s configured model.

inputs.label: temperature
inputs.description: Sampling temperature (0 = deterministic). If unset, uses the node’s configured temperature.

inputs.label: seed
inputs.description: Seed for deterministic sampling (-1 = random/unset). If unset, uses the node’s configured seed.

inputs.label: max_iterations
inputs.description: Maximum internal ReAct iterations (safety cap). Higher values allow more tool-use steps.

inputs.label: max_input_tokens
inputs.description: Optional per-agent input token budget (max_input_tokens). When set, overrides the run's default _limits.max_input_tokens for the agent sub-run.

inputs.label: system
inputs.description: Optional system prompt for this agent instance (high priority instructions).

inputs.label: prompt
inputs.description: The task/user prompt for the agent to solve.

inputs.label: tools
inputs.description: Allowlist of tool names this agent can call (defense-in-depth; runtime still enforces allowlists).

inputs.label: structured_output
inputs.description: Optional JSON Schema object (type=object) the final answer must conform to.

inputs.label: context
inputs.description: Optional explicit context object for the agent (e.g. {messages:[...]}). If provided, it can override inherited run context.

outputs.label: result
outputs.description: Structured final agent result (answer + metadata/tool calls depending on agent).

outputs.label: tool_calls
outputs.description: Best-effort list of tool call requests extracted from the agent scratchpad trace (post-run). For real-time tool observability, subscribe to the ledger/node_traces stream.

outputs.label: tool_results
outputs.description: Best-effort list of tool results extracted from the agent scratchpad trace (post-run). For real-time tool observability, subscribe to the ledger/node_traces stream.

outputs.label: scratchpad
outputs.description: Runtime-owned execution trace/scratchpad for observability (LLM/tool steps, timings).

data.label: SEMANTIC EXTRACTOR RULES V1
data.literalValue:
# Semantic Triple Writer Prompt (v4 optimized)

Task: extract **high-signal semantic knowledge** from the input as triples.

Output (strict):
- Output **ONLY** a JSON object that matches the enforced schema: `{"triples":[...]}`
- Do **not** output chat/completion wrappers (`id`, `choices`, `usage`, etc.).
- No prose, no markdown.

Prefixes (use CURIEs everywhere possible):
- `dcterms:` `http://purl.org/dc/terms/`
- `schema:` `https://schema.org/`
- `skos:` `http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#`
- `cito:` `http://purl.org/spar/cito/`
- `rdf:` `http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#`
- `ex:` instance namespace (your only custom namespace)

Triple rules (each item in `triples`):
- `s`,`p`,`o` are **strings**.
- `s` and `p` MUST be CURIEs: `prefix:local`.
- `o` SHOULD be a CURIE when it’s an entity; otherwise a literal string (ISO-8601 for times/dates; full URL allowed).
- Always set `type` ∈ {`semantic`,`episodic`,`relational`}.
- If `type=="episodic"`, set `time` to the event time (ISO-8601 date-time).
- Set `src` (short provenance token like hostname/doc-id/user/system) and `conf` in `[0,1]` (1.0 if explicit; ≤0.6 if inferred/guessed).

ID policy (instances):
- Create new entities only as `ex:{kind}-{kebab-case}` (lowercase, stable).
- Reuse IDs; don’t create duplicates.

Ontology choice (minimal + high adoption; keep cohesion):
- Documents/structure/metadata → `dcterms:`
- Concepts/definitions/taxonomy → `skos:`
- Agents/general entities/content links → `schema:`
- Claims/evidence/citations → `cito:`
- Class membership → `rdf:type`

Minimal completeness (for every `ex:*` entity you introduce):
- Add `rdf:type` and exactly one primary label:
  - documents/sections → `dcterms:title`
  - concepts → `skos:prefLabel`
  - other entities/agents → `schema:name`

Preferred predicates (use before inventing `ex:*` predicates):
- Structure: `dcterms:hasPart`, `dcterms:isPartOf`, `schema:nextItem`, `schema:previousItem`
- Metadata: `dcterms:identifier`, `dcterms:created`, `dcterms:modified`, `dcterms:creator`, `dcterms:publisher`, `dcterms:subject`
- Content links: `schema:about`, `schema:mentions`, `dcterms:references`, `schema:sameAs`
- Concepts: `skos:definition`, `skos:altLabel`, `skos:broader`, `skos:narrower`, `skos:related`, `skos:exactMatch`, `skos:closeMatch`
- Evidence: `cito:supports`, `cito:disagreesWith`, `cito:usesDataFrom`, `cito:providesDataFor`, `cito:extends`, `cito:discusses`, `cito:confirms`

Extraction policy:
- Assert only what the input supports (open-world; no negatives; no guessing).
- Each triple = one atomic fact (no “and”, no multi-clause objects).
- Prefer fewer, higher-value triples over exhaustive coverage.
- If no standard predicate fits, use an `ex:` predicate and set `conf <= 0.6`.

- `rdf:` `http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#`

Triple rules (each item in `triples`):
- `s`,`p`,`o` are **strings**.
- `s` and `p` MUST be CURIEs: `prefix:local`.
- `o` SHOULD be a CURIE when it’s an entity; otherwise a literal string (ISO-8601 for times/dates; full URL allowed).
- Always set `type` ∈ {`semantic`,`episodic`,`relational`}.
- If `type=="episodic"`, set `time` to the event time (ISO-8601 date-time).
- Set `src` (short provenance token like hostname/doc-id/user/system) and `conf` in `[0,1]` (1.0 if explicit; ≤0.6 if inferred/guessed).

ID policy (instances):
- Create new entities only as `ex:{kind}-{kebab-case}` (lowercase, stable).
- Reuse IDs; don’t create duplicates.

Ontology choice (minimal + high adoption; keep cohesion):
- Documents/structure/metadata → `dcterms:`
- Concepts/definitions/taxonomy → `skos:`
- Reality (events/places/actors/actions/outcomes) → `schema:`
- Claims/evidence/citations → `cito:`
- Class membership → `rdf:type`

Reality extraction (prevents “orphaned events”):
- For each distinct **happening** in the input, create an event node `ex:event-*` with `rdf:type` = `schema:Event` and a short `schema:name`.
- Anchor each event with at most one primary `schema:location` and one time anchor (`schema:startDate` or `schema:temporalCoverage`) when present.
- Attach actors with `schema:participant` (and `schema:organizer` only when explicitly an organizer).
- Attach explicit outcomes/stats with `schema:result` (no implied causality).

Minimal completeness (for every `ex:*` entity you introduce):
- Add `rdf:type` and exactly one primary label:
  - documents/sections → `dcterms:title`
  - concepts → `skos:prefLabel`
  - other entities/agents → `schema:name`

Preferred predicates (use before inventing `ex:*` predicates):
- Structure: `dcterms:hasPart`, `dcterms:isPartOf`, `schema:nextItem`, `schema:previousItem`
- Metadata: `dcterms:identifier`, `dcterms:created`, `dcterms:modified`, `dcterms:creator`, `dcterms:publisher`, `dcterms:subject`, `schema:genre`
- Context & anchors: `schema:about`, `schema:mentions`, `dcterms:references`, `schema:sameAs`, `schema:location`, `schema:temporalCoverage`
- Action & participants: `schema:participant`, `schema:organizer`, `schema:result`, `schema:instrument`, `schema:startDate`, `schema:endDate`
- Concepts: `skos:definition`, `skos:altLabel`, `skos:broader`, `skos:narrower`, `skos:related`, `skos:exactMatch`, `skos:closeMatch`
- Evidence: `cito:supports`, `cito:disagreesWith`, `cito:usesDataFrom`, `cito:providesDataFor`, `cito:extends`, `cito:discusses`, `cito:confirms`

Extraction policy:
- Assert only what the input supports (open-world; no negatives; no guessing).
- Each triple = one atomic fact (no “and”, no multi-clause objects).
- Prefer fewer, higher-value triples over exhaustive coverage.
- Avoid graph explosion: create location/time/participant nodes only for **primary** context (skip incidental mentions).
- Disambiguate roles: `dcterms:creator` = author/outlet; `schema:participant` = people/orgs in the story.
- If no standard predicate fits, use an `ex:` predicate and set `conf <= 0.6`.

data.label: Python translate json -> ttl string
data.literalValue:
import json
from collections import defaultdict

def triples_to_turtle_v1(triples_data):
    # 1. Group triples by Subject
    # Structure: grouped[subject][predicate] = [object1, object2, ...]
    grouped = defaultdict(lambda: defaultdict(list))
    
    for triple in triples_data:
        s = triple['s']
        p = triple['p']
        o = triple['o']
        grouped[s][p].append(o)

    # 2. Define Mappings for Predicates (to match your Version 1 shorthand)
    # Maps full JSON predicate -> Condensed output predicate
    pred_map = {
        "dcterms:title": "title",
        "dcterms:description": "desc",
        "skos:prefLabel": "label",
        "dcterms:references": "refs",
        "rdf:type": "type",
        "dcterms:hasPart": "hasPart",
        "dcterms:creator": "creator",
        "dcterms:date": "date",
        "dcterms:subject": "subject",
        "cito:discusses": "discusses",
        "cito:supports": "supports",
        "cito:providesDataFor": "providesDataFor",
        "cito:usesDataFrom": "usesDataFrom",
        "cito:extends": "extends",
        "cito:cites": "cites",
        "schema:name": "name",
        "schema:url": "url"
    }

    output_lines = []

    # 3. Iterate through grouped data to build strings
    for subject, predicates in grouped.items():
        line_parts = [subject] # Start with Subject (e.g., ex:news-cnn)
        
        # Build list of "predicate objects" strings
        # e.g. ['title "Breaking News"', 'refs ex:news-cnn, ex:news-ap']
        pred_strings = []
        
        for p, objects in predicates.items():
            # Apply mapping or strip common prefixes if no mapping exists
            clean_pred = pred_map.get(p, p)
            
            formatted_objects = []
            for o in objects:
                # formatting logic for Objects
                if o.startswith("ex:") or o.startswith("dcterms:"):
                    # It's an entity/node -> No quotes
                    formatted_objects.append(o)
                elif p == "rdf:type" and o.startswith("schema:"):
                    # Special case for types: "schema:NewsEvent" -> "NewsEvent"
                    formatted_objects.append(o.replace("schema:", ""))
                elif o.startswith("http"):
                    # It's a raw URL -> Enclose in <> or quotes? 
                    # Your version 1 didn't show URLs, but quotes are safer for simple text
                    formatted_objects.append(f'"{o}"')
                else:
                    # It's a literal string/date -> Enclose in quotes
                    formatted_objects.append(f'"{o}"')
            
            # Join multiple objects with commas (e.g., refs ex:a, ex:b)
            obj_str = ", ".join(formatted_objects)
            pred_strings.append(f"{clean_pred} {obj_str}")
        
        # Join all predicate-object groups with semicolons
        full_statement = " ; ".join(pred_strings)
        
        # End with a dot
        output_lines.append(f"{line_parts[0]} {full_statement} .")

    return "\n".join(output_lines)

# Example Usage with your variable 'input_json'
# Assuming input_json is defined as the list of dictionaries
if __name__ == "__main__":
    # For testing purposes, paste your input_json here or ensure it's in scope
    # input_json = [...] 
    
    # Check if input_json exists (mimicking your environment)
    try:
        result = triples_to_turtle_v1(input_json)
        print(result)
    except NameError:
        print("Error: 'input_json' variable not found. Please define it before running.")
